&gt; Well, as you say, this is a subjective area, but I&#39;ll list some of the
&gt; reasons why I think the first example is convoluted:
&gt; 
&gt; - It&#39;s using a reverse logic: enter catch -&gt; good, proceed as usual
&gt; -&gt; bad. This is highly counter-intuitive.
&gt; - It has an empty catch statement (always a code smell in my book),
&gt; hence the necessity to add a no-op call or a comment to say &quot;it&#39;s okay, I
&gt; know what I&#39;m doing&quot;.
&gt; - It doesn&#39;t express its intent clearly (if I show you three tests
&gt; with try/catch, you won&#39;t be able to tell right away which ones test for
&gt; exceptions and which ones don&#39;t).
&gt; 
&gt; On the other hand, the annotated code expresses its intent clearly (it
&gt; almost reads as plain English), doesn&#39;t drown the signal in noise and is
&gt; much shorter.
&gt; 
&gt; It&#39;s actually a perfect example where annotations are clearly an improvement
&gt; over the &quot;old way&quot;, in my opinion...
